Using facet wrap gives a clear picture of the trends of each species without any visual interference from other species.

ggplot(data=p)+
  geom_point(mapping= aes(bill_length_mm,flipper_length_mm))+
  facet_wrap(~ species,nrow=2)
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

The loess line in this plot shows that for each species, there is a slow but consistent positive relationship between bill length and flipper length and then a sudden rise in the positivity of the relationship. Sudden changes in plots sometimes indicate the prevalence of subgroups within the datta. If I had to guess, I would say the sudden rise in positivity is because of sex differences withing each penguin species.

Part 2 of Assignment 2.

Delete all records with at least one missing component.

not_missing <- na.omit(p)
fin.data <- not_missing %>%
  filter(species == "Adelie" | species =="Gentoo",
         island =="Biscoe" | island=="Torgersen",
         body_mass_g < 5000 & body_mass_g > 3500) %>%
  mutate(BMI= body_mass_g / 4000) %>%
  select(-X,-sex,-year,-body_mass_g)
plot4 <- ggplot(fin.data, aes(x = bill_depth_mm, color=species)) +
          geom_histogram( 
                         alpha = 0.3, 
                         position = "identity", 
                         binwidth = 0.2)+
  facet_grid(species~.)
pplot4 <- plot4 +labs(x="Bill Depth mm",y="Count",
                      title = "Bill Depth by Species.")
pplot4

scatter02 <- ggplot(fin.data, aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = flipper_length_mm, 
                              color = species, 
                              size = BMI)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5)
scatter02 <- scatter02 +labs(x="Bill Length mm",y="Flipper Length mm",
                      title = "Bill Length to Flipper Length")
scatter02

#plot_grid(scatter02, pplot4, labels=c("A", "B"),ncol = 2, nrow = 1)

It is clear that Adelie penguins have smaller flipper and bill lengths on average compared to Gentoo penguins. Despite this, Adelie penguins have much larger bill depth on average compared to Gentoo penguins. An interesting observation is that Adelie penguins also appear to have much more BMI variation compared to Gentoo penguins. Almost all Gentoo penguins appear to have BMIs above 1.0 while there are a noticeable amount of Adelie penguins with BMIs above and below 1.0.
